      "title": "Interconnection Order No. 2023 Compliance Plan and Tariff Review",
      "text": "Sara Keegan Assistant General Counsel\n\nInterconnection Order No. 2023 Compliance Plan and Tariff Review\n\nInterconnection Issues Task Force (IITF) March 1, 2024\n\nThinh Nguyen Senior Manager, Interconnection Projects\n\nAgenda\n\n Tariff Review Schedule  Overview of Interconnection Procedures in the Current Tariff  Overview of New NYISO Interconnection Procedures – OATT Attachment HH – and Conforming Tariff Revisions\n\n• Updated and new tariff revisions are posted with the meeting materials N \n Conceptual Changes to the Compliance Plan since the February 16, \n2024 IITF Meeting \n Next Steps \n\n##### Tariff Approach\n\n At the December 14, 2023, Operating Committee (OC) meeting, the NYISO presented to stakeholders its comprehensive compliance plan for Order No. 2023, which presentation is attached as Appendix A.\n\n• The NYISO has modified aspects of the compliance plan presented on December 14, 2023 in response to stakeholder feedback. Any such modifications will be identified in upcoming meetings. \n The NYISO has posted draft tariff language to implement this comprehensive plan \non February 6, 2024 and February 16, 2024. \n This presentation summarizes the NYISO’s overall tariff approach and highlights \nconceptual changes from the 2/16 IITF Presentation. \n Conceptual changes/revisions from the 2/16 IITF Presentation and discussion \npoints for today’s meeting are noted in red. \n\n### Interconnection Procedures – Current Tariff\n\nInterconnection Procedures in Current NYISO OATT\n\n The NYISO’s interconnection procedures for generating facilities and transmission projects subject to the Class Year are currently established across multiple attachments of the OATT\n\n• Att. S – Rules to Allocate Responsibility for the Cost of New Interconnection Facilities; \n• Att. X – Standard Large Facility Interconnection Procedures; and \n• Att. Z – Small Generator Interconnection Procedures. \n\n The NYISO OATT contains separate interconnection requirements for Transmission Projects in OATT Att. P and for transmission expansion and load projects in the body of the OATT.\n\n### New NYISO Interconnection Procedures - Attachment HH\n\nNew OATT Attachment HH  New OATT Attachment HH includes the interconnection procedures for the new Cluster Study Process – the Standard Interconnection Procedures.\n\n• Attachment HH will consolidate the existing requirements from OATT Attachments S, X, and Z, as revised for the new Cluster Study Process and compliance with Order No. 2023. \n• Attachments S, X, and Z will remain in the tariff for the limited purposes of the NYISO’s completing Class Year 2023 and performing the transition to the new Cluster Study Process.  The NYISO is not proposing revising its Transmission Interconnection Procedures in Attachment P to the OATT or the transmission expansion rules in the body of the OATT, except for any conforming revisions needed to account for the new Attachment HH rules. \n\nNew OATT Attachment HH  As detailed in the following slides, new Attachment HH uses the general structure of the current Standard Large Facility Interconnection Procedures in Attachment X as revised to incorporate:\n\n• New Cluster Study Process elements; \n• Applicable rules from Attachments S and Z; and \n• Order No. 2023 pro forma revisions.  As the new Cluster Study mirrors in large part the current Class Year Study, many of the existing Class Year Study and related cost allocation requirements in OATT Attachment S will remain largely the same in Attachment HH \n• Revisions to these provisions (including the Existing System Representation, ATBA, ATRA, Class Year Deliverability Study, Additional SDU Study, and headroom rule) are required to align with the new process elements, including more explicit separation between the Phase 1 (formerly Part 1) and the Phase 2 (formerly Part 2) studies. \n\n The existing, stand-alone Small Generator Interconnection Procedures will largely be replaced by the new procedures.\n\n• The Fast Track Process and 10 kV Inverter Process will be included in the new Attachment HH. \n\nNew OATT Attachment HH Structure • 40.1 – Definitions o Consolidated definitions from Attachments S, X, and Z and Order No. 2023 o Revised Definitions (Site Control, Overage Cost, Balancing Authority Area, Balancing Authority etc.)\n\n• 40.2 - Effective Date, Scope, and Application of Standard Interconnection Procedures o New rules and rules from Att. X 30.2 and Att. S 25.10 o Clarification of OATT Limitation of Liability rules to Standard Interconnection Procedures \n• 40.3 -Transition Rules o New rules and rules from Att. X 30.5 o Revised rules for treatment of Additional SDU Study for CY23 Projects o Revised treatment of impact of ongoing system impact and feasibility studies for entering Transition Cluster Study Process \n• 40.4 - Pre-Cluster Study Process Procedures (i.e., Heatmap and Pre-Application Report) o New rules and rules from Att. Z 32.1 and Order No. 2023 Pro Forma 6.1 \n• 40.5 - Cluster Study Process Start Date/ Application Window/ Interconnection Requests/ Interconnection Service Options o New rules and rules from OATT 30.3 and Order No. 2023 Pro Forma 3.4.2 o Revised rules for addressing deficiencies in Transmission-Owner specific information o Updated timeframe for developer to address material change in Site Control from 10 to 15 Business Days \n\nNew OATT Attachment HH Structure (cont.) • 40.6 - Queue Position/ Modification/ Withdrawal/ Withdrawal Penalties o New rules and rules from OATT 30.3 and 30.4 o Clarified in COD extension rules that TO can determine as part of Cost Estimate Update replacement equipment for equipment identified in interconnection study that is no longer available o Clarified timing of review of material modification request for technological changes\n\n• 40.7 - Customer Engagement Window (including Cluster Study Project List, Scoping Meeting, and Physical Infeasibility Screening)/ Phase 1 Entry Decision Period o New rules and rules from OATT 30.3 and Order No. 2023 Pro Forma 3.4.5. \n• 40.8 - Affected Systems within New York Control Area and External Affected Systems o New rules and rules from OATT 30.3 and Order No. 2023 Pro Forma 3.6 and 9. o Clarified that NYISO will allocate Affected System Upgrade Facility costs consistent with existing process for System Upgrade Facilities and clarified cost estimates rules for such upgrades \n• 40.9 - Cluster Study Overview/ NYISO Minimum Interconnection Standard/ NYISO Deliverability Interconnection Standard/ Cluster Study Cost Allocation Rules o New rules and rules from Att. X 30.3 and Att. S 25.1, 25.2, 25.4 and 25.5 \n• 40.10 - Phase 1 Study/ Existing System Representation/ Annual Transmission Baseline Assessment / Phase 1 Study Scope and Procedures/ Phase 2 Entry Decision Period o New rules and rules from Att X 30.8 and Att. S 25.5, 25.6 o Clarified conclusion date for study process and date NYISO would provide required info for TOs to commence Phase 1 Study. \n\nNew OATT Attachment HH Structure (cont.) • 40.11 - Phase 2 Study / Annual Transmission Reliability Assessment o New rules and rules from Att X 30.8 and Att. S 25.5, 25.6 o Clarified conclusion date for study process and stakeholder process at conclusion of Phase 2 Study process\n\n• 40.12 – Cluster Baseline Assessment (CBA) and Cluster Project Assessment (CPA) (formerly “ATBA and ATRA”) \n• 40.13- Cluster Study Deliverability Study o Rules from Att. S 25.7 o Clarified External CRIS Request process rules. \n• 40.14 - Additional SDU Study o Rules from Att. S 25.5 o Revised Additional SDU Study to limit study to Highways/Other Interface SDUs and to clarify study within new process \n• 40.15 - Final Decision Period/ Additional SDU Study Decision Period o New rules and rules from Att. S 25.8 o Revise developer options in Final Decision Period to remove option to defer ERIS election in cases of Additional SDU Studies \n• 40.16 - Security Forfeiture; Future Cost Responsibility o Rules from Att. S 25.8 \n\nNew OATT Attachment HH Structure (cont.) • 40.17 - Headr",
